Preheat your oven to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Chop the @potatoes{450} into 2cm wide wedges (no need to peel). Halve the @bell pepper{1} and discard the core and seeds. Slice into thin strips.

Pop the wedges onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @olive oil{2} for the dressing, season with @salt{1/4%tsp} and @ground black pepper{}, then sprinkle over the @cumin seeds{1}. Toss to coat, then spread out in a single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden, ~{25-35%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, in a medium #bowl{}, combine the @korma curry paste{50%g} and @panko breadcrumbs{10%g}. Add the @lamb mince{300%g}, then season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{} and mix together with your hands.

Shape into mini sausage shapes, 6 per person. Flatten to make koftas.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw mince.

Put the koftas and peppers on another baking tray. Drizzle with oil and season with salt and pepper.

Bake on the middle shelf of your oven until browned on the outside and cooked through, ~{15-20%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The koftas are cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Meanwhile, trim the @baby gem lettuce{1}, halve lengthways, then thinly slice. Pick the @mint{1} leaves from their stalks and roughly chop (discard the stalks).

Wash up the bowl used for the koftas. Add the @Greek style natural yoghurt{75%g}, olive oil (see pantry for amount) and mint to the (now empty) bowl.

Season with salt and pepper and mix together. Set your mint yoghurt aside.

Heat a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat with a knob of @?butter{} (if you have any) or a drizzle of @olive oil{}.

Lay in one of the @super soft tortillas with whole wheat{4} and cook until golden brown, about ~{1%minute} each side. Transfer to a #plate{} or #cutting board{}, cover with #foil{} and repeat the process with the remaining tortillas (2 per person).

Add the baby gem lettuce to the bowl with the minty yoghurt and mix to combine.

In another small bowl, combine half the @mango chutney{80%g} with the @mayonnaise{2}.

When everything's ready, spread the remaining mango chutney towards the bottom of each wrap.

Top with some salad, a few strips of pepper and 3 koftas per wrap. Roll up tightly to enclose the filling and repeat.

Serve your kathi rolls with the wedges and any remaining salad and peppers alongside. Pop the mango mayo on the side for dipping.

Enjoy!